nals. From legal relief organizations to family reunification specialists, she shows us how different aid workers may choose to work for, with, or against unaccompanied immigrant youth, deciding whether they should be treated as refugees, child dependents, or, in some cases, criminals. Ruehs-Navarro highlights how aid workers, and the systems they represent, often harm the very children they are designed to help. Unaccompanied brings into focus the plight of immigrant youth at the border, illuminating our failure to manage the human casualties of a growing crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBorder securityzUnited States. 0aChild welfarezUnited States. 0aChildren of immigrantsxEducationzUnited States. 0aNeoliberalismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aAdolescence.  aAgency.  aAsylum.  aAttorneys.  aBorder Security.  aBureaucracy.  aChild Abuse.  aChild Welfare.  aChildhood.  aCriminalization.  aCrimmigration.  aDependency.  aDetention.  aDiscrimination.  aEducation.  aEmbodiment.  aEthical dilemmas.  aFamilies.  aFamily reunification.  aHomelessness.  aHumanitarianism.  aImmigrant Youth.  aImmigration policy.  aImmigration relief.  aInstitutional analysis.  aIntersectionality.  aLabor.  aLegal system.  aLife Course.  aMigration decisions.  aNeoliberalism.  aOffice of Refugee Resettlement.  aPersonal Responsibility.  aProfessional norms.  aQualitative Methods.  aRace.  aResistance.  aRole strain.  aSocialization.  aSpecial Immigrant Juvenile VIsa.  aStorytelling.  aTattoos.  aTeachers.  aTransnational Families.  aTrauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075162840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978147983